SIMPLE: pod
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -pod
<hw>-pod</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>. <ety>[See <er>Foot</er>.]</ety> <def>A
combining form or suffix from Gr. <grk>poy`s</grk>, <grk>podo`s</grk>,
<xex>foot</xex>; <as>as, deca<ex>pod</ex>, an animal having ten feet;
phyllo<ex>pod</ex>, an animal having leaflike feet; myria<ex>pod</ex>,
hexa<ex>pod</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pod</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pod
<hw>Pod</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Probably akin to
<ets>pudding</ets>, and perhaps the same word as <ets>pad</ets> a
cushion; cf. also Dan. <ets>pude</ets> pillow, cushion, and also E.
<ets>cod</ets> a husk, pod.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A bag; a
pouch.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A capsule of plant, especially a
legume; a dry dehiscent fruit. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Angiospermous</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A considerable number of animals
closely clustered together; -- said of seals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Pod auger</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>pod
bit</b></col></mcol>, <cd>an auger or bit the channel of which is
straight instead of twisted.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pod</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pod
<hw>Pod</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Podded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Podding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To swell; to fill; also, to
produce pods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>-poda</ent>⟦br⟧
